<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-327-880  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 327 880.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Communications of the ACM  June 1989 v32 n6 p677(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Assn. for Computing Machinery, Inc. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The worm story. (the Internet worm)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT/><NOTE>Only Text is presented here; see printed issues for graphics.andO;</NOTE><TEXT>THE WORM STORYandM;When a worm program invaded the Internet last November, it did more thaninfect thousands of computers nationwide.andP;  It held the potency of computercrime up for public scrutiny.andM;Unlike accounts of espionage schemes or teenage pranks, the attack on theInternet was different.andP;  The story made front page news both here and abroad.andO;The action made politicians reconsider protective legislation.andP;  Theconsequence made computer professionals all too aware of the dangerousweaknesses in systems security.andP;  The offense, so dastardly, made the crimefiles of Dick Tracy.andM;In the past eight months, the worm incident has drawn some of the industry'sleading experts to dissect its form, analyze industry response and preventfuture attacks.andP;  In this issue, we have pulled together some of the mostrecent work on the subject.andP;  The preceding President's Letter and Viewpointsoffer commentaries on the computer industry's course of action, while LegallySpeaking examines the civil and criminal implications of the deed.andM;The following special section offers a four-sided view of the Internet wormitself.andP;  Eugene Spafford discusses its structure; Mark Eichin and Jon Rochlischronicle its spread; Donn Seeley details its password algorithm; and theCornell commission summarizes its investigation into the  worm creation ofgraduate student Robert Morris, Jr.andM;For all the facts and evidence the comprise the plot, this worm story is onestill in search of an ending...andO;</TEXT></DOC>